content.description: Bouldery, thin and hard vertical climbing off the ground. The roof has big holds and is easier than it looks. Holds get scarce on the slab above. Crux at about 2/3 height.

tricky undercling up high

Admin edit: Rock 106 has lately become a crag favorite and sees a lot of traffic now. Rock 106 and Klingon both became a grade harder a few years ago when the Klingon flake fell off. I heard a bottle jack might have helped mother nature shed this flake, but who cares; the flake was scary, the route is harder and better now. 18 feet of tough boulder moves on thin crimps leads to a temporary respite uncerclinging the flake, then some cruxy long moves to crimps at the third bolt. a few bolts of easier climbing lead to the second crux, a huge move off a decent undercling.
Powerful climbing on pockets. has some long moves between fortuitously good mono pockets. Said to be brilliant climbing.
Thin, tough boulder problem down low, then direct over the Klingon roof.
content.location: Between Spock and Klingon

content.description: delicate mantle move
Said to have a very thin crux at the 5th bolt.
content.location: just right of the popular 11a, Stay Tuned

content.description: Vertical thin climbing low and then steep climbing with better holds above.
content.location: This is one of the climbs in the really tall and blank looking section of the crag just left of middle. Route is to the right of Return of the King.

content.description: LO anchors half way up the wall Hard move out of the roof
Grape Ape is a good crack in a dihedral with a small roof 2/3 of the way up. It is a pretty decent crack which has been the subject of past bolting controversies.
content.location: Obvious bolted crack in theÂ right facing corner on the right side of the wall.

content.description: Probably the best 11a here. Starts up a left facing flake and turns the roof to the left. This climb stars out crimpy and hard, then juggy and overhanging mid-way. finishes with some good, balancy slab climbing.
content.location: Starts underneath the roof on the far right side of the crag. This is on the other side of the fence.

content.description:
Originally a gear route that was retrobolted, The Force follows a right facing flake system. At the last bolt, a long reach for a crappy rail followed by a spooky heel hook move and reach for the large sandbag perched at the top of this route. If the grade feels hard for the route which it will, remember this used to be done on gear alone! (Probably with some TR rehearsal)

This is a really good route. I'm surprised it doesn't get done more often. Give it a try.
content.protection: bolts to chains. can also be lead on gear. bring a light rack with singles up to a #3 Camalot, and your smallest stuff + 1 set of nuts... big brass nuts.
content.location: Towards the right side of the crag, but before the fence. Look for a right facing flake two routes to the right of Grape Ape, the right-facing dihedral.

content.description: I believe the name refers to a tire that the FA party stood on to reach the starting holds. Now there is a pile of rocks under the route that one can stand on, although I have seen it done without, but at a higher grade. Bouldery moves off the deck lead to a flake system and some very fun climbing.
content.location: 2nd route to the right of Chicken Spread, look for the pile of cheater rocks.

climbs.name: The Dull Sickle (Hair of the Dog)

content.description: Thin, bouldery, start.  It's the crux.  Then a bit pumpy to the ledge.  Little bit of a crux at the top.
content.location: There's a dispute weather Curt Shannon did the first ascent.  If he didn't I did.  Maybe Curt will chime in on this cause he was gone from the scene when we started climbing.

content.description: Clip the first bolt of Chicken Spread, then take the bolt line that trends right. The climbing is fun, technical, and footwork intensive. One of the easiest 5.11's at Dishman, but still fair for the grade.
Start to the right of Slave Labor and finish at Slave Labor chains.
content.protection: Bolts, shares chains with Slave Labor
content.location: Dead Vermin is on the far right end of the cliff and shares chains with Slave Labor.

content.description: left slanting crack to headwall
content.protection: 10 stainless bolts to chains. Thanks to Andrew Bower for the crag upkeep! The memorial near here is for Andrew.
content.location: right end

content.description:
One of the most infamous sandbags in Spokane. The climbing is good, but it may feel hard for 5.9.

The crux is about 1/2 way up the wall, before you go over the lip.

HARD FOR THE GRADE
content.location: Start just left of the 8 foot tall granite spire near the middle of the wall.

content.description: Left slanting crack, left of Free Installation, that finishes on Dull Sickle (Hair of the Dog)

Start on an undercling located at the back center of the cave. Come out onto the lip with a textbook crimp. Get yourself over to some fine slopers to the above right. Get a nice high foot and get to that satisfying undercling. Keep on going you're almost there.
content.location: Walk along the trail through the canyon towards the Main Dishman climbing wall. When you can see the wall, you should see a trail branching off and heading up rightward (westward) out of the canyon. There's a little clearing halfway up the hill where a large rock formation that looks like a giant's eyebrow sits. Hard to miss it. It's very enticing.

content.description:
In the interest of adding to the Dishman database, I'm borrowing this description, as I have only flailed on this climb thus far.

"This route starts out on perfect overhanging granite features, then pulls a roof and leads into some sequential slab climbing to the chains of Slave Labor. The route was recently resurected after the blanket of moss covering it was removed. The lack of inactivity is not because it's a bad route (it's actually very good), it's probably the 12a grade (still a big grade around here) that keeps folks away."
content.location: Right side of the crag, by the tree. Ends at Slave Labor's chains.

content.description: Sidepulls on small rt. facing flakes leads to pockets above. The feet are pretty small.
content.location:
Blue Chip is the climb just to the left of

Wings.

content.description: This short route on the far left of the crag doesn't see much traffic.
A good 5.11 route that starts out of the hole in the ground to the right of Grape Ape.
content.protection: Listed as a mixed route in Bland's book, but fully bolted now.
content.location: First route to the right of Grape Ape (the easy to spot right-facing dihedral right-of-center on the wall).

content.description: Bouldery start, between Touch of Grey and Spock. Finishes on Touch of Grey. Doesn't get done very often, so leave a comment if you've tried it.
content.protection: Bolted, finish on Touch of Grey anchor.
content.location: Between Spock and Touch of Grey.

content.description: One of the many good 11a's at Dishman. Head up the left facing flake system.
content.location: second bolt line in from the left side of the crag.

content.description:
Some burly moves off the ground get you to the first bolt, then to the crux a bolt higher.  Hint:  It's a lunge.

Honestly, I don't remember a damn thing about the climbing after the crux.  I think it was fun, but it's in the bag at that point.
content.protection: Fully bolted, at least in 2005.  Originally a mixed bolt/gear route, heavy on the gear.
content.location: About a quarter of the way down the cliff line.

content.description: The crux is pulling the roof, look for a reachy move to the left.
content.location: Far right of the crag.

content.description: One of the best hard 11's at Dishman. A tricky crux in a shallow dish down low, then brilliant climbing up high. Touch of Grey is quite hard for the grade.

This is a very cool route. You'll find delicate face moves interspersed with strenuous moves on big holds. There are two cruxy sections in the bottom third of the climb. Look for the best feet you can find(very small), and go for it!
content.protection: 9 bolts to chains. The falls from the cruxes are safe. I checked.
content.location: The third bolt line from the left side of the crag.

content.description: Long traverse move
Right facing flake left of Wings and right of Rock 106
